        q: `A 36-year-old woman has had increasing malaise for 3 weeks and urine output &lt;500 mL/day for the past 4 days. On examination, she has a blood pressure 170/112 mm Hg and peripheral edema. Urinalysis shows 1+ protein and 3+ blood, and no glucose or ketones. Urine microscopic examination shows red cells (RBCs) and RBC casts. The blood urea nitrogen is 39 mg/dL (7–18 mg/dL), the creatinine is 4.3 mg/dL (0.6–1.2 mg/dL), and antinuclear antibodies (ANA) are positive. The serum complement C1q, C3, and C4 are decreased. A renal biopsy is performed, and immunofluorescence microscopy shows the pattern of staining with antibody to C3 seen in the figure. Which of the following mechanisms is most likely the cause of her renal disease?`,
