        optionFeedback: [`The acute onset of hematuria and evidence of renal failure suggests nephritis, and the immunofluorescence staining pattern is indicative of deposition of anti-GBM antibody. This individual most likely has a form of rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis (RPGN). In severe cases, removal of the antibody from the blood by plasmapheresis is required to alleviate the acute renal failure. Chronic immunosuppression will be needed to suppress autoantibody production. `,`The lesion is not caused by an infection and is not diagnostic of acute postinfectious glomerulonephritis (GN), which is characterized by immune complex deposition in a granular immunofluorescence pattern. Antibiotics would not help even in postinfectious GN because the infection would have already resolved, and the renal lesions are not caused by ongoing infection. `,`Anti-TNF therapy is helpful for rheumatoid arthritis, inflammatory bowel disease, and other autoimmune diseases in which T cell–mediated inflammation is prominent. `,`Hepatitis vaccine is preventive, not therapeutic. Renal involvement is not common in hepatitis; when it occurs, it is caused by deposition of immune complexes in a granular pattern. `,``],
