        optionFeedback: [`Diffuse basement thickening is caused by the deposition of immune complexes in the glomerular basement membrane, and is characteristic of membranous nephropathy. This disease also causes the nephrotic syndrome, but it is more common in adults and much less responsive to steroid therapy. `,`The clinical presentation is of the nephrotic syndrome. In children, the most common cause is minimal change disease, which is characterized by normal glomerular histology (as the name of the disease implies). This disease responds well to steroid therapy. The “selective” proteinuria (preferential loss of small proteins) distinguishes this disease from most other causes of the nephrotic syndrome, in which larger proteins are also often lost. `,`Diffuse glomerular hypercellularity is a reflection of inflammation and proliferation of intrinsic glomerular cells. It is most often seen in postinfectious glomerulonephritis and lupus nephritis, both caused by extensive immune complex deposition in the glomerulus. `,`Focal sclerosis is seen in focal segmental glomerulosclerosis, which also causes nephrotic syndrome but is more common in adults, is more severe and in some cases leads to renal failure. The glomerular histology shows focal sclerosis involving portions of some, but not all glomeruli.`,``],
