        optionFeedback: [`Diffuse basement membrane thickening is seen in membranous nephropathy, which is a more frequent cause of nephrotic syndrome in adults and does not usually respond to steroids. `,`In a child with steroid-responsive nephrotic syndrome, the likely diagnosis is minimal change disease. The only electron microscopic abnormality in these cases is effacement of podocyte foot processes, a change that is often seen in association with proteinuria caused by glomerular permeability abnormalities. `,`Increased mesangial matrix is typical of diabetic nephropathy, in which matrix material is deposited in the mesangium and glomerular capillary walls, and membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis, which is associated with immune complex deposition. Both may present with nephrotic syndrome, usually in adults. `,`“Reduplication” or splitting of the GBM is seen in membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis. It is caused by mesangial cells and matrix material inserting into the capillary wall. `,``],
