        optionFeedback: [`Necrosis of glomeruli is seen in some primary glomerular diseases (FSGS, sometimes in crescentic glomerulonephritis ) but is not a consequence of hypotension because glomeruli are much less sensitive to hypoxia than are tubules. `,`Acute renal failure developing after a hypotensive episode is classic for the clinical syndrome of acute kidney injury (which pathologists call acute tubular injury). The typical lesion in severe cases is ischemic necrosis of tubules (which is why this disorder was previously called acute tubular necrosis). `,`Papillary necrosis is associated with severe acute pyelonephritis, especially in diabetics.`,`Atherosclerosis is associated with hypertension. It may be present in this case because the myocardial infarct is a result of coronary atherosclerosis. But renal atherosclerosis by itself does not cause acute oliguric renal failure. `,``],
