        q: `A 51-year-old woman has a 1-week history of dysuria and urinary frequency. On physical examination, her temperature is 38&#176;C, and she has pain on palpation over the left costovertebral angle. Laboratory findings show fasting glucose, 177 mg/dL (70-110 mg/dL); hemoglobin A<sub>1c</sub>, 9.8% (&lt; 6%); hemoglobin, 13.1 g/dL (12.0-15.2 gm/dL); platelet count, 232,200/mm<sup>3</sup> (150,000-400,000/mm<sup>3</sup>); and WBC count, 11,320/mm<sup>3</sup> (4,500-11,000/mm<sup>3</sup>). Urinalysis shows 2+ glucosuria; and no RBCs, protein, or ketones. Microscopic examination of the urine shows numerous WBCs, and a urine culture is positive for Escherichia coli.  Which of the following complications is most likely to develop in this patient?`,
