        optionFeedback: [`Polycystic kidney disease presents with hematuria, hypertension, and progressive renal failure, not evidence of infection. Grossly, the kidneys are often massively enlarged and the parenchyma is almost entirely replaced by cysts. `,`In hypertension, there is interstitial fibrosis and loss of tubules, but this is caused by ischemia not chronic infection, so inflammatory infiltrates are not prominent and there are no white cells in the urine. `,`The main renal complication of systemic lupus erythematosus is glomerular disease; interstitial fibrosis and tubular atrophy are uncommon. `,`The history of frequent urination and fever suggests a urinary tract infection. The presence of white cells in the urine is diagnostic for pyelonephritis and the ultrasound image is consistent with a chronic lesion (loss of renal parenchyma). The histology of the nephrectomy specimen is diagnostic of chronic pyelonephritis. Vesicoureteral reflux is a major predisposing condition because it allows the retrograde passage of bacteria from the lower urinary tract to the kidneys. `,``],
