        q3: [],
        option: [`Deposition of immune complexes with streptococcal antigens`,`Formation of antibodies against glomerular basement membrane`,`Hematogenous dissemination of septic emboli`,`Hypersensitivity reaction to ampicillin`,`Renal tubular cell necrosis caused by bacterial toxins`],
        optionFeedback: [`Poststreptococcal glomerulonephritis involves glomeruli and causes hematuria, hypertension and variable proteinuria. WBCs in the urine are uncommon. A skin rash may be seen as part of acute streptococcal infection, but it is usually not present by the time renal symptoms appear. `,`Anti-glomerular basement membrane antibodies also cause nephritis (proteinuria, hematuria, renal failure); WBCs in the urine are uncommon.`,`Systemic emboli may lodge in the kidneys and cause renal infarction, which is manifested by hematuria. If the emboli are infected (as may occur in bacterial endocarditis) they may produce abscesses. There is no association with skin rash. `,`The onset of mild hematuria and proteinuria associated with skin rash following administration of ampicillin (and several other drugs) is strongly suggestive of a drug reaction, causing tubulointerstitial nephritis. (Skin rash is a frequent manifestation of drug hypersensitivity.) The presence of WBCs, especially eosinophils, in the urine supports this diagnosis. The confirmatory test is removal of the offending agent, which should lead to complete resolution. `,``],
        optionStyleType: `st-upper-alpha`,
