        q: `A 63-year-old man has noted increasing back pain for 7 months. He has had three respiratory tract infections with Streptococcus pneumoniae  during the past year. On examination, he has pitting edema to his thighs. Laboratory studies show total serum protein, 9.6/dL (6.0-7.8 g/dL); albumin, 2.5 g/dL (3.5-5.5 g/dL); creatinine, 3 mg/dL (0.6-1.2 mg/dL); blood urea nitrogen, 28 mg/dL (7-18 mg/dL); and fasting glucose, 79 mg/dL (70-110 mg/dL). Urinalysis shows proteinuria of 4 g/24 h (&lt;150 mg/24 h), but no glucosuria or hematuria. Abdominal CT scan shows enlarged kidneys without cysts or masses; multiple well-circumscribed lytic lesions are noted in the vertebral column. A renal biopsy specimen stained with H&amp;E shows deposits of amorphous pink material within glomeruli, interstitium, and small arteries. Which of the following diseases is he most likely to have?`,
