        q: `A 5-year-old girl develops cramping abdominal pain and diarrhea 4 days after eating a hamburger, chili, and ice cream at a home barbecue. The next day, she has decreased urine output. On physical examination, there are petechial hemorrhages in the skin. Laboratory findings show a serum creatinine level of 2.2 mg/dL (0.6-1.2 mg/dL) and blood urea nitrogen level of 20 mg/dL (7-18 mg/dL). CBC shows hemoglobin, 10.8 g/dL (10.5-13.5 g/dL); hematocrit, 32.4% (33-40%); platelet count, 64,300/mm<sup>3</sup> (150,000-400,000/mm<sup>3</sup>) and WBC count, 6,480/mm<sup>3</sup> (3,800-14,000/mm<sup>3</sup>). The peripheral blood smear shows schistocytes, and the serum <small>D</small>-dimer level is elevated. Urinalysis shows 2+ hematuria; and no protein or glucose. A renal biopsy specimen shows small thrombi within glomerular capillary loops. This clinical picture develops most commonly after infection with which of the following organisms?`,
        q2: ``,
        q3: [],
        option: [` Candida albicans `,`Clostridium difficile `,` Escherichia coli `,`Proteus mirabilis `,`Staphylococcus aureus `],
        optionFeedback: [`Candida  is a fungus that causes mucocutaneous lesions and, in immunosuppressed individuals, systemic infection. It is not associated with glomerular lesions or hemolytic anemia. `,`C. difficile  causes pseudomembranous colitis in patients treated with antibiotics that deplete the normal intestinal flora.`,`The clinical presentation is diagnostic of hemolytic uremic syndrome (HUS). This is a form of thrombotic microangiopathy caused by Shiga-like toxin produced by E. coli . The pathogenesis involves widespread damage to the endothelium caused by the toxin. This triggers the formation of microvascular thrombi, consumption of platelets (causing thrombocytopenia), and microangiopathic hemolytic anemia (caused by fragmentation of RBCs as they traverse microvasculature narrowed by thrombi). The <small>D</small>-dimer is a fibrin breakdown product; its elevation indicates disseminated coagulation. Renal failure results from injury to glomeruli. Other forms of thrombotic microangiopathy include thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura (TTP) and atypical HUS caused by excessive activation of complement.`,`Proteus  is a frequent cause of urinary tract infection but is not associated with disseminated coagulation, hemolytic anemia, or vascular thrombi.`,``],
