        q: `A 55-year-old man has had back pain and dark-colored urine for the past month. On physical examination, there is tenderness over the right costovertebral angle. Urinalysis shows a pH of 6 (4.5-8.0); specific gravity, 1.015 (1.002-1.030); 2+ hematuria; and no protein, glucose, or ketones. Microscopic examination of the urine shows numerous RBCs, a few WBCs, and no casts or crystals. The figure shows the representative gross appearance of the renal lesion. Which of the following driver mutations is most likely to be found in this lesion?`,
