        option: [`Inactivation of VHL , with overexpression of VEGF`,`Inactivation of WT1 , with overexpression of genes involved in renal differentiation`,`Inactivation of APC , with overexpression of beta-catenin`,`Inactivation of RB  with loss of G<sub>1</sub>-S control`,`Inactivation of PTEN , with activation of PI3K/AKT tyrosine kinases `],
        optionFeedback: [`The history of flank pain and hematuria is suspicious for renal cell carcinoma, and the morphology is characteristic (yellowish tumor because of lipid-filled cells, often with areas of hemorrhage and vascular invasion). A frequent genetic lesion in this tumor is deletion or inactivation of the VHL  gene. The VHL protein is a ubiquitin ligase that is responsible for degradation of many proteins, including the transcription factor HIF-1α. Increased levels of HIF-1α lead to overproduction of growth factors, including VEGF, which promotes angiogenesis and tumor growth.`,`Inactivation of the WT1  gene is associated with Wilms tumor, a tumor associated with abnormal differentiation of the renal blastema because of reduced, not over, expression of genes associated with differentiation. The tumor presumably develops because of over-proliferation of primordial cells. `,`Inactivation of APC  is associated with carcinoma of the colon.`,`Mutational inactivation of RB  occurs in retinoblastomas and osteogenic sarcomas. High-risk HPVs also cause functional inactivation of RB .`,``],
